The '''Bibliography of Aeolian Research''' (BAR) is a comprehensive bibliography focused on the study of the detachment, transport, and deposition of sediments by wind.<ref name=BAR>{{Citation | last =Warren | first = A. | last2 = Gill | first2 = T.E. | last3 = Stout | first3 = J.E. | title = Bibliography of Aeolian Research |publisher = USDA-Agricultural Research Service, Lubbock, Texas | url = https://www.lbk.ars.usda.gov/wewc/biblio/bar.htm | accessdate = 2014-07-19}}</ref>
Aeolian research is a sub-discipline of the physical sciences that focuses on the activity of the winds, with an emphasis on the winds' ability to interact with and shape the surface of the Earth and other planets.<ref name=Stout>{{Citation| last = Stout| first = J.E.| last2 = Warren| first2 = A.| last3 = Gill| first3 = T.E.| title =Publication trends in aeolian research: an analysis of the Bibliography of Aeolian Research| journal =Geomorphology| volume =105| issue =1-2| pages =6–17| year =2009| doi =10.1016/j.geomorph.2008.02.015}}</ref> Aeolian research spans a broad array of disciplines and may include the study of [[aeolian processes]] and associated [[aeolian landform]]s, aeolian deposits, and sedimentary features; the study of [[wind erosion]] and its control by [[tillage]], [[cover crop]]s, [[Windbreak|shelterbelts]], and other management practices; and the study of [[mineral dust]], [[dust storm]]s and the effects of [[Particulates|fine particulate matter]] on [[climate]] and [[air quality]].
An extensive Bibliography of Aeolian Research (BAR) was constructed that contains references to every known scientific manuscript published in the field of aeolian research from 1646 to 2015.<ref name=BAR/> The BAR contains over 43,000 bibliographic citations.
As with most bibliographies, the Bibliography of Aeolian Research has benefited from past bibliographies. The BAR lists more than forty-five bibliographies that focus on at least one aspect of aeolian research and parts of these have been incorporated into the BAR. Older bibliographies are especially important because they provide a record of early publications. The oldest bibliography incorporated into the BAR is the ''Bibliography of Meteorology'' compiled by [[Oliver Lanard Fassig|Oliver Fassig]] in 1889.<ref>{{Citation | last =Fassig | first =O.L. | title =Bibliography of Meteorology | publisher =United States of America War Department, Signal Office, Washington DC | year = 1889 | pages =475}}</ref> Citations have also been extracted from the Bibliography of Eolian Geology prepared for the [[United States Department of Agriculture]] by Conrad Stuntz and Edward Free.<ref>{{Citation | last =Stuntz | first =S.C. | last2 =Free | first2 =E.E. | title =Bibliography of Eolian Geology. In: Free, E.E. (ed), The movement of soil material by wind | publisher =United States Department of Agriculture, Bureau of Soils, Washington DC | volume =Bulletin 68 | year = 1911 | pages =174–263}}</ref> Other important bibliographies that have been incorporated into the BAR include two online bibliographies that were maintained by Andrew Warren of [[University College London]] titled ''A Bibliography of Wind Erosion and Related Phenomena'' and ''A Bibliography of Desert Dunes and Associated Phenomena''.<ref>{{Citation | last =Warren | first =A. | title = A Bibliography of Desert Dunes and Associated Phenomena. In: McGinnies, W.G. and Goldman, B.J. (eds), Arid Lands in Perspective | publisher = American Association for the Advancement of Science, Washington D.C. and Tucson: University of Arizona Press | year = 1969 | pages =75–100}}</ref> The Bibliography of Aeolian Research contains more citations extracted from these two bibliographies than from any other source. Citations were also obtained from a monthly internet posting called ''Aeolian Papers of the Month'', a list of published papers compiled each month from 1996-2001 by Thomas Gill at the [[Texas Tech University]].
Editors Andrew Warren, John Stout and Thomas Gill collected bibliographic citations by searching databases and extracting citations from recent publications.<ref name=BAR/> New entries included citations to scholarly articles, books, theses, dissertations, and reports.
