'''Keith Hope Shackleton''' [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (16 January 1923 &ndash; 17 April 2015) was a British painter who concentrated on [[Landscape art|landscape]] views and animals. He has also produced [[limited edition]] prints. He was a friend of the [[conservation movement|conservationist]] and fellow painter [[Peter Scott]], with whom he travelled to [[Antarctica]]. Like Scott, he went to [[Oundle School]]. He was also a presenter on the [[BBC]] children's television programme ''[[Animal Magic (TV series)|Animal Magic]]'' and of the [[Children's ITV]] series ''Animals in Action'', produced by [[Anglia Television]] using footage from its ''[[Survival (TV series)|Survival]]'' series.
A [[retrospective]] exhibition of his "Polar Art", depicting creatures and scenery from both the [[Arctic]] and Antarctic was open at the [[Scott Polar Research Institute]] in May and June 2007.
Shackleton was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2012 Birthday Honours for services to the conservation of wildlife.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=60173|supp=y|page=21|date=16 June 2012}}</ref>
He died peacefully on 17 April 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://announcements.telegraph.co.uk/deaths/190025/shackleton|title=SHACKLETON|work=telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>
